se against virus","Inhibits viral protein assembly","Prevents viral RNA synthesis","Blocks viral entry into host cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENeuraminidase inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing the release of new viral particles from infected cells\u003C/strong\u003E. They inhibit the viral neuraminidase enzyme, which normally cleaves sialic acid residues that tether newly formed viral particles to the host cell surface. Without this cleavage, viral particles remain bound to infected cells and cannot spread to infect new cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEntry inhibitors work through \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking viral entry into host cells\u003C/strong\u003E by preventing viral attachment to host cell receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents viral RNA synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of nucleoside analogues which interfere with viral genome replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits viral protein assembly\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; Neuraminidase inhibitors act after viral assembly is complete, not during the protein assembly process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeuraminidase inhibitors work through direct antiviral action rather than immunomodulation (i.e. by \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulating a host immune response against a virus\u003C/strong\u003E). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy preventing viral spread, neuraminidase inhibitors can reduce the severity and duration of influenza symptoms when given early in the course of infection. They are effective against both influenza A and B viruses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neuraminidase inhibitors prevent the release of new viral particles from infected cells by blocking viral neuraminidase enzyme.","Neuraminidase inhibitors are effective against both influenza A and B viruses.","Common examples of neuraminidase inhibitors include oseltamivir and zanamivir."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54514"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17061"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54514"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T08:56:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T08:57:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9751"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69057"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descript